I am building SENTINEL — a tool that monitors MAVLink drone 
communication and detects attacks. This post explains the 
problem it is trying to solve, in plain terms, before I get 
into the technical details of how it works.

## What is MAVLink

MAVLink is the protocol drones use to communicate with their 
ground control stations. When you fly a drone and see its 
position on a map, its battery level, its speed — all of that 
information is being sent over MAVLink. When you tell the drone 
to go somewhere or land — that command goes over MAVLink.

It was designed to be lightweight and reliable. It was not 
designed to be secure.

## The core problem

MAVLink version 1 has no authentication. This means any device 
on the same network can send commands to a drone and the drone 
will follow them — because there is no way for the drone to 
verify who is sending the command.

This creates some serious attack possibilities...

## What I am building

SENTINEL is a passive monitoring tool. It sits on the network 
and listens to MAVLink traffic. When something looks wrong it 
raises an alert. It never transmits anything — the drone does 
not know SENTINEL is there.

I am building it as part of VIMANA — my aerospace security 
research platform.

The code is at github.com/sumitguptaaa/sentinel — actively 
in development.

